{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17472509","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17472509"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:10+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T21:59:10+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1479"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1479"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.13,0.14,0.11,0.03,0.59]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97831"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1479","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1479"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1479"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80386"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"34"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"776"},{"type":"tags","id":"1131"},{"type":"tags","id":"2843"},{"type":"tags","id":"6351"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"824"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1058"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35351"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"97831","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/97831"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EAn 11-year-old boy presents to his general practitioner with a three month history of right knee pain. He describes the whole knee as painful, especially after a long day of exercising. His father also describes two episodes of his son\u0027s knee swelling during this period with no obvious trauma. On physical examination, there is a positive bulge test on the right and tenderness over the medial femoral condyle. There is no limitation to range of motion although it is painful. The left knee examines normally. The knee is X-rayed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Femoral fracture","Perthes disease","Osteosarcoma","Osteomyelitis","Osteochondritis dissecans"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EKnee pain in a young child has lots of causes that need excluding. \u003Cstrong\u003EFemoral fracture\u003C/strong\u003E is not seen on the X-ray and is unlikely given the lack of trauma. \u003Cstrong\u003EPerthes disease\u003C/strong\u003E generally causes hip pain but can cause referred knee pain; however it is usually in a younger child and would require a hip X-ray to diagnose. The lack of systemic features makes both \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteosarcoma\u003C/strong\u003E (lack of B symptoms or palpable lump on exam) and \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteomyelitis\u003C/strong\u003E (no fever, malaise, overlying skin changes) less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThis is \u003Cstrong\u003Eosteochondritis dissecans\u003C/strong\u003E in the typical spot (lateral edge medial femoral condyle). In this disease an osteochondral fragment can become avascular and sometime loose, leading to irritation, pain and swelling. It has an unknown cause but may be related to trauma or ischaemia.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Osteochondritis is an important cause of chronic knee pain in a young person"],"references":["Karadsheh M. Osetochondiritis dissecans [Internet]. California: OrthoBullets; 2021 [cited 2021 Jan 4]. Available from: https://www.orthobullets.com/knee-and-sports/3028/osteochondritis-dissecans."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80386"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1479